      "content": "While the \"stifling innovation\" argument has merit, it is a distraction when the stakes involve existential risk, because the cost of a single catastrophic failure far outweighs the benefits of a slightly slower rollout. Projections from the AI safety community indicate that the window to prevent unaligned AI is closing, making a robust regulatory framework not just an insurance policy but a survival necessity. In this context, the tradeoff is not between speed and safety, but between a managed, controlled development that ensures survival and an uncontrolled sprint that risks extinction.",
